ocial policy evaluation, and the impact of development policies on children and women. Shiva Kumar serves as a member of India\u2019s National Advisory Council that provides social policy and legislative inputs to Government of India for advancing the rights of disadvantaged groups. He also serves on the Board of many non-governmental organizations including the Centre for Science and Environment and the International Center for Research on Women. Shiva Kumar graduated from Bangalore University and from the Indian Institute of Management, Ahmedabad. He also has a Masters in Public Administration and a Ph.D in Political Economy and Government, both from Harvard University. Tiernan Mennen is a justice and development specialist and Founder and Director of the Haki Network. His contributions to this volume are based on a career researching and managing projects on human rights, customary law, gender-based violence, legal empowerment and land rights. He has worked in over 20 countries on all continents, with extended experience in Bolivia, South Sudan, Honduras, DR Congo, Peru, Malaysia, Hungary and with a variety of institutions, including UNDP, the World Bank, the Open Society Institute, DFID, DANIDA, USAID, and various NGOs. Tiernan is trained in mediation, has a Juris Doctor from Cornell Law and a Masters in International Economics and Development from SAIS-Johns Hopkins. Ways and Means of Realizing Social and Economic Rights and Achieving the MDGs 305 Timothy Dolan is a development consultant focusing on legal empowerment of the poor, having worked both for the Commission on Legal Empowerment of the Poor and UNDP\u2019s legal empowerment of the poor team in New York. He participated in the drafting of Making the Law Work for Everyone, the report of the Commission on Legal Empowerment of the Poor, and the 2009 Report of the Secretary-General on Legal Empowerment of the Poor and Eradication of Poverty (A/64/133). More recently, he has been working out of Cambodia, co